<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="55" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,1346,1949]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1382,1408]" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Etymology</emphasis>
: The specific epithet ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Barahona-Segovia &amp; Guzmán &amp; Barceló &amp; Pañinao-Monsálvez" authorityYear="2020" box="[593,713,1382,1408]" class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Ogcodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kunkunche">
<emphasis box="[593,713,1382,1408]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">kunkunche</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ refers to the southern Mapuche people named ‘Cuncos’. The “cuncos” or “puncos” (in mapudungun language = 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Barahona-Segovia &amp; Guzmán &amp; Barceló &amp; Pañinao-Monsálvez" authorityYear="2020" box="[750,870,1418,1444]" class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Ogcodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kunkunche">
<emphasis box="[750,870,1418,1444]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">kunkunche</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) were a sedentary indigenous people, frequently considered to be the southern-most branch of the Mapuche people. They lived in southern 
<collectingCountry box="[1175,1236,1454,1480]" name="Chile" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">Chile</collectingCountry>
from the Maullín River to the northern part of Chiloé and the neighboring islands. This indigenous people developed agriculture, cultivating several crops including potatoes and corn. Also, they were dedicated to recollecting marine mollusks and hunting marine fishes, sea lions and other marine mammals. The name “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Barahona-Segovia &amp; Guzmán &amp; Barceló &amp; Pañinao-Monsálvez" authorityYear="2020" box="[966,1086,1562,1588]" class="Insecta" family="Acroceridae" genus="Ogcodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kunkunche">
<emphasis box="[966,1086,1562,1588]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="55">kunkunche</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” was chosen for this spider fly species because this indigenous people were the group most hostile to the Spanish colonizers, and this represents the persistence of the new species described herein in the fragmented landscape that currently dominates the main Chiloé Island.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
